				<td class="main" valign="top">

									<div style="{color:red; font-size:32px; text-align:center;}">Problems with Tenancies</div>
									<div style="{font-size:26px; text-align:center;}">(Landlords)</div>
								<br>
								<p>
									Even with the best of intentions, relationships between tenants and landlords may not always run smoothly, so we have developed a guide that we hope will assist you in managing your investment.
								</p>
								<p>
									<a name="table">
									</a></p><li><a href="/#1">Utilities Charges</a></li>
									<li><a href="/#2">Telephones</a><br></li>
									<li><a href="/#3">Meter Box Problems</a></li>
									<li><a href="/#4">TV Antennae and Telephone Line Connections</a></li>
									<li><a href="/#5">Property Condition</a></li>
									<li><a href="/#6">Rental Bonds</a></li>
									<li><a href="/#7">Tenant's Objections</a></li>
								<p></p>
								<p class="tenantheader">
       									 <a name="1">
									Utilities Charges
								</a></p><a name="1">
								<p>
									When doing renovations or repairs, landlords (or tradespeople) may have the gas and electricity temporarily connected and occasionally, forget to have them disconnected when the work is finished. As a nice gesture to the tenant, they may be left connected to save the tenant the connection fee, advising the tenant to have the meter read and to change the billing details. However, what if the tenant 'forgets' to do this and later the landlord receives a bill for the usage?
									Utilities are considered to be personal bills and not attached to the property so in cases like this, an agent cannot take the tenant to the tenancies tribunal to recover the amount so there is very little that can be done.
									The rule then is, never come to an informal agreement with the tenant regarding the payment of utilities. The tenant should establish accounts under his own name.
								</p>
								</a><p style="{text-align:center;}"><a name="1">
									</a><a href="/#table">^TOP^</a>
								</p>
								<p class="tenantheader">
       									 <a name="2"> 
									Telephones
								</a></p><a name="2">
								<p>
									A telephone can be bought and left for the tenant or leased from the provider in the usual arrangement. What happens if the telephone 'vacates the premises' with the tenant? Whose responsibility is it if the phone breaks down and needs repairing or replacing?
								</p>
								<p>
									It may be easier to define responsibility if the tenant provides his own phone.
								</p>
								</a><p style="{text-align:center;}"><a name="2">
									</a><a href="/#table">^TOP^</a>
								</p>
								<p class="tenantheader">
       									 <a name="3">
									Meter Box Problems
								</a></p><a name="3">
								<p>
									Landlords are advised to have flats metered separately. This avoids bitter disputes between tenants about who pays what amount.
								</p>
								</a><p style="{text-align:center;}"><a name="3">
									</a><a href="/#table">^TOP^</a>
								</p>
								<p class="tenantheader">
       									 <a name="4">
									TV Antennae and Telephone Connections
								</a></p><a name="4">
								<p>
									These days tenants expect that a landlord will provide a tv antenna and a telephone connection point. If the tenant pays to have a telephone line installed it will remain after the tenant vacates - to the benefit of the landlord. Removing a tv antenna is an awkward job so that will probably remain too when the tenant leaves.
								</p>
								<p>
									Although both these items are for the benefit of the tenant and therefore not strictly the responsibility of the landlord, it is probably wise for a landlord to have both these connections installed. Apart from adding to the capital value of the property and making it a better rental proposition, it will remove all chances of dispute over responsibility and costs.
								</p>
								</a><p style="{text-align:center;}"><a name="4">
									</a><a href="/#table">^TOP^</a>
								</p>
								<p class="tenantheader">
       									 <a name="5">
									Property Condition
								</a></p><a name="5">
								<p>
									The most common source of disputes between landlords and tenants arises from a landlord's refusal to maintain the property in a liveable condition. Some landlords feel that they shouldn't bother about the condition of the property as "a tenant will only wreck it".
								</p>
								<p>
									Apart from allowing a valuable asset to deteriorate, if the landlord treats the property with disdain he is likely to attract the type of tenant who will be right at home in that environment. The Residential Tenancies Act re-affirms the common law standard in which the landlord is responsible for 'fair wear and tear'. The property has to be fit for human habitation, fit to live in
								</p>
								</a><p style="{text-align:center;}"><a name="5">
									</a><a href="/#table">^TOP^</a>
								</p>
								<p class="tenantheader">
									<a name="6">
									Rental Bonds
								</a></p><a name="6">
								<p>
									Refund of the rental bond (or security deposit) is the most frequent cause of dispute between landlords and tenants. The bond should never be considered as the landlord's money. In all states of Australia it is held in trust for the landlord against any future breaches of the tenancy agreement.
								</p>
								<p>
									Four weeks rent is the usual bond amount but it can be more for prestigious properties or when it is the landlord's own home. The bond amount must be entered on the tenancy agreement and the tenant must be given a receipt.
								</p>
								<p>
									The bond is then lodged with the state bond authority after the cheque is cleared from the agent's Trust Account. It is an offence for the landlord not to forward the bond to the state bond authority.
								</p>
								<p>
									At the end of the tenancy, if the rent is paid up to date and there are no claims for damage or any breach of the tenancy agreement, the bond is refunded to the tenant.
								</p>
								<p>
									If the landlord lodges a claim against the bond, the tenant can sign a release of the money or if the tenant refuses to sign, the landlord can claim directly from the bond authority.
								</p>
								</a><p style="{text-align:center;}"><a name="6">
									</a><a href="/#table">^TOP^</a>
								</p>
								<p class="tenantheader">
									<a name="7">
									Tenant's Objections
								</a></p><a name="7">
								<p>
									If the tenant does object to the claim of his bond, he may ask for his case to be heard in the Residential Tenancies Tribunal. The Tribunal has jurisdiction to hear matters where the claim does not exceed $3000.
								</p>
								<p>
									Many landlord-tenant disputes are resolved by negotiation before a hearing takes place. It often pays the landlord to go to the Tribunal anyway to get agreement in writing that is legally enforcable.
								</p>
								<p>
									In most cases, it is the agent who successfully mediates the dispute and the Tribunal is avoided.
								</p>
								<p>
									An agent is a professional who can negotiate in a calm and impersonal way on behalf of his client. Landlords are often too emotionally involved to argue successfully in the Tribunal and tend to win fewer cases because proper leases were often not prepared, condition reports were missing, expenses could not be documented, etc.
								</p>
								</a><p style="{text-align:center;}"><a name="7">
									</a><a href="/#table">^TOP^</a>
								</p><p>&nbsp;</p>
							
